text: We present a partially reversible U-Net for efficiently generating and segmenting a partially normalized volumetric image based on convolutional neural networks, which has high memory utilization of 256-1,000 per second.

The network is trained by training some sub-networks on a portion of a large image using a convolutional neural network, and then doing the convolutional loss function with a loss function which includes a Gaussian kernel, a mean-shift kernel, and a softmax kernel which we reverse.
This result has been obtained for real-world data for real-world images.
The partial U-net is very efficient despite its complexity: on an ordinary computer it consumes 256-1,000 times less memory than conventional convolutional neural networks.
